docs.abstract: Tech companies say consumers prefer being shown ads that are relevant to them. But a professor’s research shows they trade data for those ads not because of convenience but resignation.
docs.snippet: Tech companies say consumers prefer being shown ads that are relevant to them. But a professor’s research shows they trade data for those ads not because of convenience but resignation.
docs.lead_paragraph: The diapers ad that shows up on your computer when you are expecting a child. The coupon on your smartphone for a fast-food chain you just walked past. The sneaker offer appearing in your mailbox after you sign up to run a race.

headline.main: Sharing Data for Deals? More Like Watching It Go With a Sigh
headline.print_headline: Giving Up Data Privacy With a Sigh

docs.abstract: It was fun while it lasted. Cryptocurrencies soared and then they crashed. But true aficionados believe the underlying blockchain still has potential.
docs.snippet: It was fun while it lasted. Cryptocurrencies soared and then they crashed. But true aficionados believe the underlying blockchain still has potential.
docs.lead_paragraph: PALO ALTO, Calif. — Last year around this time, a toy called a cryptokitty sold for $170,000. A real estate agent remade himself as CoinDaddy, producing cryptocurrency-themed music videos. The man behind a company called Ripple became for a moment richer than Mark Zuckerberg. Kids barely out of high school were buying Lamborghinis because of a crypto meme. Experts went on CNBC to say Bitcoin was going to reach $100,000 per coin.

headline.main: Remember Bitcoin? Some Investors Might Want to Forget
headline.print_headline: Amid Crypto Wreckage, Die-Hards Remain True

docs.abstract: If Walmart, Lowe’s and other companies win their property tax appeals, homeowners and small businesses will have to pay more or live with smaller town budgets.
docs.snippet: If Walmart, Lowe’s and other companies win their property tax appeals, homeowners and small businesses will have to pay more or live with smaller town budgets.
docs.lead_paragraph: WAUWATOSA, Wis. — With astonishing range and rapidity, big-box retailers and corporate giants are using an aggressive legal tactic to shrink their property tax bills, a strategy that is costing local governments and school districts around the country hundreds of millions of dollars in lost revenue.

headline.main: As Big Retailers Seek to Cut Their Tax Bills, Towns Bear the Brunt
headline.print_headline: As Stores Wiggle Out of Taxes, Towns Bear Brunt

docs.abstract: Humu, a Silicon Valley start-up, applies data-driven lessons in human resources to the goal of improving employee satisfaction.
docs.snippet: Humu, a Silicon Valley start-up, applies data-driven lessons in human resources to the goal of improving employee satisfaction.
docs.lead_paragraph: MOUNTAIN VIEW, Calif. — Technology companies like to promote artificial intelligence’s potential for solving some of the world’s toughest problems, like reducing automobile deaths and helping doctors diagnose diseases. A company started by three former Google employees is pitching A.I. as the answer to a more common problem: being happier at work.

headline.main: Firm Led by Google Veterans Uses A.I. to ‘Nudge’ Workers Toward Happiness
headline.print_headline: Toward a Happier Office With Data-Driven Nudges

docs.abstract: The industry sold more than 17 million vehicles for the fourth straight year. But it is relying more on fleet sales, and economic winds are not favorable.
docs.snippet: The industry sold more than 17 million vehicles for the fourth straight year. But it is relying more on fleet sales, and economic winds are not favorable.
docs.lead_paragraph: As they recorded another year of strong United States sales, automakers said Thursday that they saw little cause for concern in the months ahead. But a closer look shows signs of strain emerging on several fronts.

headline.main: U.S. Auto Sales Put Up a Big Number, but Show Signs of Strain
headline.print_headline: Car Sales Streak Is Reaching Its Limits

docs.abstract: Schools are not required to use the same terminology in their offers. And an “award” could mean a grant — or a loan. “Celebrate,” one expert says. “Then, decide.”
docs.snippet: Schools are not required to use the same terminology in their offers. And an “award” could mean a grant — or a loan. “Celebrate,” one expert says. “Then, decide.”
docs.lead_paragraph: High school students opening their college financial aid offers may be excited to see that they have received an “award.” After all, it sounds like a prize, but “award” has its own meaning in the student aid world.

headline.main: Before Deciding on a College, Look Closely at the Financial Aid Letter
headline.print_headline: Congratulations on Your College ‘Award.’ Or Is It a Loan?

docs.abstract: The hotel chain hasn’t said how many of the 500 million customers affected by a data breach had their passport numbers stolen. But the State Department and privacy experts disagree on the danger.
docs.snippet: The hotel chain hasn’t said how many of the 500 million customers affected by a data breach had their passport numbers stolen. But the State Department and privacy experts disagree on the danger.
docs.lead_paragraph: It has become a familiar dance: A company reports a data breach, and you dutifully change your passwords, ask for a new credit card and hope your information doesn’t end up for sale on the dark web. But the hack that last week engulfed Marriott — and 500 million of its customers — has added a new step: Your passport might be at risk, too.

headline.main: Marriott Hack Adds Passport Headache, but Its Intensity Is in Dispute
headline.print_headline: In Hacking Of Hotels, New Loot: Passports

docs.abstract: Shoeleather aims to connect journalists outside New York, Washington, Los Angeles and San Francisco with editors across the country.
docs.snippet: Shoeleather aims to connect journalists outside New York, Washington, Los Angeles and San Francisco with editors across the country.
docs.lead_paragraph: In recent years, as local news organizations have been decimated by layoffs and industry consolidation, communities across the country have complained  that journalists who come into their towns and cities too often produce shallow or misrepresentative reporting.

headline.main: Better Local Journalism, by Local Reporters, Is the Goal of a New Database
headline.print_headline: A Tool for Better Reporting Far From the Media Hubs

docs.abstract: Authorities are using harsh methods to target people posting criticism of the government on a social media platform that is blocked in the country, extending online censorship beyond China’s borders.

docs.lead_paragraph: SHANGHAI — One man spent 15 days in a detention center. The police threatened another’s family. A third was chained to a chair for eight hours of interrogation.

headline.main: Twitter Users in China Face Detention and Threats in New Beijing Crackdown
headline.print_headline: He Was Chained to a Chair in China. What Was His Offense? Posting on Twitter.

docs.abstract: Lu Shaye said in an op-ed for The Hill Times that Canadians applied “double standards,” viewing their own country’s laws as having to be observed, but not China’s.
docs.snippet: Lu Shaye said in an op-ed for The Hill Times that Canadians applied “double standards,” viewing their own country’s laws as having to be observed, but not China’s.
docs.lead_paragraph: BEIJING — China’s ambassador to Canada has said that “Western egotism and white supremacy” were behind calls for Beijing to release two detained Canadians, further straining relations between the countries after the arrest in Canada last month of a Chinese technology executive.

headline.main: China’s Ambassador to Canada Blames ‘White Supremacy’ in Feud Over Arrests
